The paper deals with learning policies for robot control, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The use of simulation and domain randomization for policy learning suggests a focus on machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of Bayesian optimization and the focus on transferability suggest a focus on control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the experimental validation of the proposed approach on a swing-up task suggests a focus on computer vision (cs.CV) for perception and tracking of the object being swung up.
